Telegram bot registers bad parkers and sends data to local POLICE department.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name></name></author><category term="project" /><summary type="html">Telegram bot registers bad parkers and sends data to local POLICE department.</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">How I use Jekyll</title><link href="https://reskir.github.io/2018/12/29/jekyll-for-blogging.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="How I use Jekyll" /><published>2018-12-29T06:15:15+00:00</published><updated>2018-12-29T06:15:15+00:00</updated><id>https://reskir.github.io/2018/12/29/jekyll-for-blogging</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://reskir.github.io/2018/12/29/jekyll-for-blogging.html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;150&quot; src=&quot;/assets/jekyll-logo-b3c1ec4d30dc8f0af93274e8781d760a1f4c93c1aee292667e791cd548f3c329.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My experience with jekyll started with simple blog about urbanism and city development (&lt;a href=&quot;//urbanistas.lt&quot;&gt;https://urbanistas.lt&lt;/a&gt;). You can find all source files on github &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/reskir/urban_blog&quot;&gt;github project page&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 id=&quot;perks-of-using-jekyll-for-your-projects&quot;&gt;Perks of using Jekyll for your projects:&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No backend/databases&lt;/strong&gt; (yes, I consider this as pros).&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Static files&lt;/strong&gt;, all you need is html + css and sometimes some simple javascript logic (for slider f.ex.);&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Markdown&lt;/strong&gt; - it is easy to document and write posts&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plugins&lt;/strong&gt; - jekyll has some awesome plugins for SEO, asset management and etc.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hosting&lt;/strong&gt; - it is easy to host, even github pages can host jekyll website&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h4 id=&quot;what-packages-and-tools-i-am-using&quot;&gt;What packages and tools I am using&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For my blogs I usually reuse the same plugins, the most useful I found are these:&lt;/p&gt;

